Begun by reading the provided data into R

metadata <- read.csv("diabimmune_16s_t1d_metadata.csv")
dim(metadata)
## [1] 777   6

###Naration. The loaded metadata contains 777 observations and 6 variables.With 5 categorical variables and 1 numeric variable.

Followed by changing the structure of categorical variables to factors

metadata$Gender <- as.factor(metadata$Gender)  
metadata$Case_Control <- as.factor(metadata$Case_Control)
metadata$Delivery_Route <- as.factor(metadata$Delivery_Route)

###Naration. For Statistical modeling purposes, I changed variables to factors.

###Naration 53% of the overall babies used in the study were male, while the remaining 43% were female. Among these, 91.5% were delivered normally (vaginal) whereas the remaining 8.5% were delivered through Cesarean operation. The over all mean age at collection of the babies under study was 483 days with a standard deviation of 295.

Did graphical Representation for the data

boxplot(metadata$Age_at_Collection~ metadata$Gender, main="Boxplot for Age at Collection by Disease Status", xlab="Disease Status", 
        ylab="Age")

###Naration There was no skeweness in the metadata considering Disease Status against Age. Basing on the box plot of Age against Disease Status, the metadata was found to be well distributed and divides the data

Previously had read the following data into R

metadata <- read_csv("diabimmune_16s_t1d_metadata.csv")

I afterwards imported the data to create a Phyloseq Object as follows

taxa <- read_tsv("diabimmune_t1d_16s_otu_table.txt", skip = 1)
## 
## -- Column specification --------------------------------------------------------
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   ConsensusLineage = col_character()
## )
## i Use `spec()` for the full column specifications.
dim(taxa)
## [1] 2240  779

I then extracted the OTU table

otu <- taxa %>% select(1:778)
names(otu)[1] <- "OTU_ID"
otu <- column_to_rownames(otu, var = "OTU_ID")

Followed by extracting the taxonomy data table as follows

taxonomy <- taxa %>% select(`#OTU ID`, ConsensusLineage) %>%
  separate(ConsensusLineage, c("Domain", "Phylum", "Class", "Order", "Family", "Genus", "Species"), sep = ";")
names(taxonomy)[1] <- "OTU_ID"
taxonomy <- column_to_rownames(taxonomy, var = "OTU_ID")

Then changed OTU and taxonomy data frames to matrices

otu.matrix <- as.matrix(otu)
taxa.matrix <- as.matrix(taxonomy)

Later imported metadata as follows

metadata4 <- column_to_rownames(metadata, var = "Sample_ID")

Then Created a Phyloseq Object

OTUtable <-  otu_table(otu.matrix, taxa_are_rows = TRUE)
Taxonomytable <-  tax_table(taxa.matrix)
samplemetadata <-  sample_data(metadata4)
phylo_object = phyloseq(OTUtable, Taxonomytable, samplemetadata)

##Task Four

Created a DESeq Object

phylo_object <- phyloseq(otu_table(otu.matrix + 1,taxa_are_rows=TRUE),tax_table(taxa.matrix))
sample_data(phylo_object) <- metadata4
sample_data(phylo_object)[,"Gender"] <- as.factor(unlist(sample_data(phylo_object)[,"Gender"]))
sample_data(phylo_object)[,"Case_Control"] <- as.factor(unlist(sample_data(phylo_object)[,"Case_Control"]))
sample_data(phylo_object)[,"Delivery_Route"] <- as.factor(unlist(sample_data(phylo_object)[,"Delivery_Route"]))
casecontrol = phyloseq_to_deseq2(phylo_object, ~ Case_Control)
## converting counts to integer mode
##   it appears that the last variable in the design formula, 'Case_Control',
##   has a factor level, 'control', which is not the reference level. we recommend
##   to use factor(...,levels=...) or relevel() to set this as the reference level
##   before proceeding. for more information, please see the 'Note on factor levels'
##   in vignette('DESeq2').

Performed Differential Abundance using DEseq2

casecontrol = DESeq(casecontrol, test="Wald", fitType="parametric")

Obtained Results table

res = results(casecontrol, cooksCutoff = FALSE)
alpha = 0.01
casetab = res[which(res$padj < alpha), ]
casetab = cbind(as(casetab, "data.frame"), as(tax_table(phylo_object)[rownames(casetab), ], "matrix"))
